Experience
Research Experience
2016–2023 Research Associate,Beijing National Laboratory for Condensed Matter
Physics, Institute of Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing, China.
In this period, my primary research focuses on using mean ﬁeld theory to numeri-
cally solve the Gross-Pitaevskii (GP) equation to investigate the dynamic evolution
and nonlinear matter wave interference eﬀects of Bose-Einstein condensates (BECs).
I study the inﬂuence of various factors such as gravity potential, micro-particle inter-
action strength, initial momentum of the wave function, and initial phase diﬀerence
between condensates on the density and phase distribution of BEC wave functions.
Additionally, I propose a model to study the impact of macroscopic eﬀective momen-
tum and energy brought about by the macroscopic distribution of micro-particles on
the evolution of the wave function. I also evaluate the eﬀectiveness of the GP equation
based on experimental results.

Research Plan
1. Study of Supersymmetry: My plan is to use ultra-cold atomic molecules
in an optical lattice to construct a Bose-Fermi mixture, in order to further
investigate supersymmetry in low-energy physics and search for methods to
experimentally verify it.
2. Study of particles with imaginary momentum: My plan is to study par-
ticles with imaginary momentum under certain conditions, explore the physical
signiﬁcance of imaginary momentum, and search for methods to experimentally
verify it.
3. Study of Bose-Einstein Condensate (BEC) in microgravity: My plan is
to compare the evolution of BEC wave functions in microgravity environments
versus those where gravity cannot be ignored, as well as investigate the various
properties of BECs aﬀected by gravity.
